plants, animals, ideas, and beliefs traversing it, the Silk Road is now considered both a metaphor of globalization and an early example of it.Teaching the Silk Road highlights the reasons to incorporate this material into courses and shares resources to facilitate that process. It is intended for those who are not Silk Road or Asian specialists but who wish to embrace a global history and civilizations perspective in teaching, as opposed to the more traditional "world history" view that shows impacts of other societies on Europe. The work explores both classroom and experiential learning and is intentionally interdisciplinary. Each essay focuses on pedagogical strategies or themes that teachers can use to bring the Silk Road into the classroom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aTrade routesxStudy and teaching (Higher)zAsia. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aHistory : World History. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aBai, Tongdong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlson, Marybeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiamant, Hirsh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, Robert W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, Ronald K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrost, Marcia J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuo, Gang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHe, Zhang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Jacqueline M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Jacqueline M